e, England":"Birmingham, Warwickshire, Engleska, United Kingdom"},"cs":{"about 1235–4 August 1265":"okolo 1235–4. srpna 1265","1235–1265":"1235–1265","1237–1275":"1237–1275","1262–1332":"1262–1332","1264–Male":"1264–Zesnulý","1175–1240":"1175–1240","1264":"1264","1275":"1275","1175":"1175","1240":"1240","1262":"1262","4 August 1265":"4. srpna 1265","1259":"1259","1237":"1237","1235":"1235","1332":"1332","1265":"1265","about 1235":"okolo 1235","before 1262":"před 1262","Tethmay, Ireland":"Irsko","England":"Anglie","Evesham, Worcestershire, England":"Evesham, Worcestershire, Anglie","Birmingham, Warwickshire, England":"Birmingham, Warwickshire, Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"about 1235–4 August 1265":"omkring 1235–4. august 1265","1235–1265":"1235–1265","1237–1275":"1237–1275","1262–1332":"1262–1332","1264–Male":"1264–Afdød","1175–1240":"1175–1240","1264":"1264","1275":"1275","1175":"1175","1240":"1240","1262":"1262","4 August 1265":"4. august 1265","1259":"1259","1237":"1237","1235":"1235","1332":"1332","1265":"1265","about 1235":"omkring 1235","before 1262":"før 1262","Tethmay, Ireland":"Irland","England":"England","Evesham, Worcestershire, England":"Evesham, Worcestershire, England","Birmingham, Warwickshire, England":"Birmingham, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"about 1235–4 August 1265":"circa 1235–4 augustus 1265","1235–1265":"1235–1265","1237–1275":"1237–1275","1262–1332":"1262–1332","1264–Male":"1264–Overleden","1175–1240":"1175–1240","1264":"1264","1275":"1275","1175":"1175","1240":"1240","1262":"1262","4 August 1265":"4 augustus 1265","1259":"1259","1237":"1237","1235":"1235","1332":"1332","1265":"1265","about 1235":"circa 1235","before 1262":"vóór 1262","Tethmay, Ireland":"Ierland","England":"England","Evesham, Worcestershire, England":"Evesham, Worcestershire, England","Birmingham, Warwickshire, England":"Birmingham, Warwickshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1235–4 August 1265":"about 1235–4 August 1265","1235–1265":"1235–1265","1237–1275":"1237–1275","1262–1332":"1262–1332","1264–Male":"1264–Deceased","1175–1240":"1175–1240","1264":"1264","1275":"1275","1175":"1175","1240":"1240","1262":"1262","4 August 1265":"4 August 1265","1259":"1259","1237":"1237","1235":"1235","1332":"1332","1265":"1265","about 1235":"about 1235","before 1262":"before 1262","Tethmay, Ireland":"Ireland","England":"England","Evesham, Worcestershire, England":"Evesham, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom","Birmingham, Warwickshire, England":"Birmingham, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bermingham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Liam, Sinead.","Irish (of English origin): variant of   Birmingham  . This form of the surname is found mainly in Ireland.","History: The Bermingham family take their surname from lands held at what is now a great city in the West Midlands of England, but it was brought to Ireland as early as the 12th century. The Norman baron Robert de Bermyngeham was a follower of Strongbow (see   Clare  ); his name is found on a number of Irish charters between 1175 and 1179. The family was also known as <i>Mac Fheorais</i> (see   Corish  ) in Ireland, named for Piers (Gaelic <i>Feoras</i>) de Bermyngeham, the father of Robert."],"variants":[{"name":"Birmingham","meanings":["English: habitational name from Birmingham in the West Midlands. In Domesday Book the name is already found as <i>Bermingeham</i>, but it seems likely that it was originally <i>Beornmundingahām</i> ‘homestead (Old English <i>hām</i>) of the people of (<i>-inga-</i>) <i>Beornmund</i>’, a personal name composed of the elements <i>beorn</i> ‘young man, warrior’ + <i>mund</i> ‘protection’. This surname is established in Ireland (see   Bermingham  )."]},{"name":"Corish","meanings":["Irish:","shortened form of <i>Mac Fheorais</i> ‘son of Piers’. The name was borne by a Connacht family descended from Piers de Bermingham, second lord of Athenry in Galway (died <i>c.</i> 1309). Compare   Bermingham  .","shortened form of <i>Mac Muirghis</i> ‘son of <i>Maurice</i>’, a personal name introduced to Ireland by the Normans. Compare   Morrissey  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":24,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"William I Bermingham was born about 1235, in England as the son of Robert Bermingham. He married Isabel Astley before 1262, in England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died on 4 August 1265, in Evesham, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 31."},"et":{"about 1235–4 August 1265":"umbes 1235–4. august 1265","1235–1265":"1235–1265","1237–1275":"1237–1275","1262–1332":"1262–1332","1264–Male":"1264–Surnud","1175–1240":"1175–1240","1264":"1264","1275":"1275","1175":"1175","1240":"1240","1262":"1262","4 August 1265":"4. august 1265",